&lt;p class=&quot;has-drop-cap&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://positiveorgs.bus.umich.edu/people/jane-dutton/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;Professor Jane Dutton&lt;/a&gt; from the University of Michigan’s Ross School of Business suggests &amp;#8220;four ways to build high-quality workplace connections&amp;#8221; — respectful engagement, support, trust — and &lt;em&gt;play&lt;/em&gt;. Play is what Cory and David focus on in this episode — why should companies set aside time for time to explore, goof off, or entertain each other with no particular outcome in mind?&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Also covered in this episode: &lt;/strong&gt;Only an hour before recording this, &lt;strong&gt;Yoast&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://yoast.com/exciting-news-yoast-joins-newfold-digital/&quot;&gt;announced&lt;/a&gt; it is being acquired by &lt;strong&gt;Newfold Digital&lt;/strong&gt; — formerly known at least in part as &lt;a href=&quot;https://robertjacobi.com/goodbye-endurance-hello-newfold-digital.html&quot;&gt;Endurance International Group&lt;/a&gt; (EIG). David and Cory share their initial thoughts with more analysis still to come.&lt;/p&gt;







